1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,700
 So these forms are kind of complicated.

2
00:00:01,700 --> 00:00:03,400
 There's a lot of little details.

3
00:00:03,400 --> 00:00:05,740
 Once we get 'em, then we'll be able to knock out forms

4
00:00:05,740 --> 00:00:08,180
 and just do form after form after form.

5
00:00:08,180 --> 00:00:12,080
 So I call this little section Post-Refresh Oops.

6
00:00:12,080 --> 00:00:16,040
 So remember this little page not so long ago

7
00:00:16,040 --> 00:00:18,520
 where I'm like, "Look, it's great, we did the CSRF

8
00:00:18,520 --> 00:00:20,340
 "and we checked it and it worked great

9
00:00:20,340 --> 00:00:24,060
 "and we put the CSRF token in and it's all good."

10
00:00:24,060 --> 00:00:27,140
 Well, it turns out from the heights of success

11
00:00:27,140 --> 00:00:30,420
 is the depths of failure, but it's not too bad,

12
00:00:30,420 --> 00:00:33,580
 not too hard to fix it, so we just gotta fix it.

13
00:00:33,580 --> 00:00:38,360
 So the problem is if the browser sends a post request

14
00:00:38,360 --> 00:00:40,500
 and it gets back a 200 and a page of HTML,

15
00:00:40,500 --> 00:00:42,400
 which is exactly what we just did,

16
00:00:42,400 --> 00:00:44,820
 and then you hit the refresh button on your browser,

17
00:00:44,820 --> 00:00:46,860
 the browser is going to resend the post request.

18
00:00:46,860 --> 00:00:48,300
 And if you go back, I said,

19
00:00:48,300 --> 00:00:50,220
 post requests are things that change.

20
00:00:50,220 --> 00:00:53,420
 So for example, if you are transferring money

21
00:00:53,420 --> 00:00:54,820
 from your account to someone else's

22
00:00:54,820 --> 00:00:57,640
 and then you hit the transfer button, it's a post,

23
00:00:57,640 --> 00:01:01,100
 and the money gets transferred, and then transfer is successful.

24
00:01:01,100 --> 00:01:04,640
 And then if you hit refresh, you're gonna post it again.

25
00:01:04,640 --> 00:01:06,760
 And so the refresh basically reruns

26
00:01:06,760 --> 00:01:08,460
 the entire previous transaction.

27
00:01:08,460 --> 00:01:11,480
 It doesn't just grab the page, it sends the post data again.

28
00:01:11,480 --> 00:01:14,020
 So if you transferred $100 in one post,

29
00:01:14,020 --> 00:01:16,840
 and you hit refresh, you're gonna transfer $100 again.

30
00:01:16,840 --> 00:01:19,340
 So what happens is is that because the browsers know

31
00:01:19,340 --> 00:01:22,460
 that posts are potentially dangerous to the server,

32
00:01:22,460 --> 00:01:24,340
 the user will get a pop-up.

33
00:01:24,340 --> 00:01:26,440
 Not from you, but from the browser to say,

34
00:01:26,440 --> 00:01:30,840
 hey, this person who built this server application

35
00:01:30,840 --> 00:01:33,060
 left you sitting on a post, and you hit refresh,

36
00:01:33,060 --> 00:01:34,760
 and I'm gonna about post it again.

37
00:01:34,760 --> 00:01:36,900
 So are you sure you really wanna do that?

38
00:01:36,900 --> 00:01:39,480
 And the problem is the user doesn't even know what a post is,

39
00:01:39,480 --> 00:01:43,000
 barely knows what's a refresh, and it looks like a mess.

40
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:45,940
 So the way to do this is you go to the page,

41
00:01:45,940 --> 00:01:49,740
 you type in 42, you hit submit query,

42
00:01:49,740 --> 00:01:52,020
 and it'll say congratulations.

43
00:01:52,020 --> 00:01:55,220
 You look at it, and then you press the refresh button.

44
00:01:55,220 --> 00:01:58,420
 The refresh button, the reload button.

45
00:01:58,420 --> 00:02:01,140
 And you press the reload button, and it says,

46
00:02:01,140 --> 00:02:03,940
 to display this page, Firefox must send information

47
00:02:03,940 --> 00:02:05,800
 that will repeat an action, such as a search order

48
00:02:05,800 --> 00:02:07,820
 confirmation that was performed earlier,

49
00:02:07,820 --> 00:02:10,040
 or a money transfer.

50
00:02:10,040 --> 00:02:12,340
 That is not a message from your application.

51
00:02:12,340 --> 00:02:14,460
 That is literally because your application

52
00:02:14,460 --> 00:02:17,060
 was a little sloppy, and Firefox is like,

53
00:02:17,060 --> 00:02:18,860
 I'm really not sure if we should do this,

54
00:02:18,860 --> 00:02:21,420
 so I'm gonna ask the user, but it doesn't exactly know

55
00:02:21,420 --> 00:02:24,760
 what to ask the user, it doesn't know what you just did.

56
00:02:24,760 --> 00:02:27,820
 And so, it's a yucky message.

57
00:02:27,820 --> 00:02:30,760
 And what we wanna do as programmers is avoid this.

58
00:02:30,760 --> 00:02:33,080
 We want all the message, all the user experience

59
00:02:33,080 --> 00:02:35,600
 coming from us, not having the browsers

60
00:02:35,600 --> 00:02:37,500
 take over some of these things.

61
00:02:37,500 --> 00:02:40,300
 And so it's just bad practice in general

62
00:02:40,300 --> 00:02:45,060
 to send a 200 post, to take a post request

63
00:02:45,060 --> 00:02:48,420
 and then send a 200 with an HTML page back, okay?

64
00:02:48,420 --> 00:02:52,100
 And so, it's just ugly, it sits in the browser ass,

65
00:02:52,100 --> 00:02:55,020
 it's out of your control, it's ugly, it's bad usability.

66
00:02:55,020 --> 00:02:56,500
 So we can do a little bit of work

67
00:02:56,500 --> 00:02:57,780
 to make this never happen.

68
00:02:57,780 --> 00:02:59,420
 So that's what we wanna do here.

69
00:02:59,420 --> 00:03:04,220
 So, the way we do this is through what we call

70
00:03:04,220 --> 00:03:07,340
 post, redirect, refresh.

71
00:03:07,340 --> 00:03:10,420
 So up next, we're gonna show how we're gonna fix all this

72
00:03:10,420 --> 00:03:13,580
 using a post, redirect, get, refresh.

73
00:03:13,580 --> 00:03:15,780
 These titles keep getting longer and longer.

74
00:03:15,780 --> 00:03:18,360
 (upbeat music)

